reviews.description: Pretty straight forward introductory accounting course. Eases you into the world of accounting well, and definitely a WAM booster unit.
A great intro course and quite an easy one in terms of marks. Tutorials were enjoyable and content was not too dry
A beginners accounting course. Make sure you understand the first few weeks as the entire course is built upon that foundation.

Mostly financial accounting & some topics on management accounting at the end. Contents are useful but can be dry because you will learn journal entries, preparing financial statements. However, with enough practice (tutorial questions), you will be fine. Exams are not challenging at all.
Study hard for the midsem because the final is very difficult
Requires lots of practice but overall good subject. Great tutor as well!

Tried quite hard for this course but I honestly did not enjoy it. The final exam was bs and I just disliked the course in general as I am not an accounting type of person. The lecturer seemed kind of fed up and gave me the impression that he didn't want to teach us. The homework was difficult for me. The online quizzes was the only good thing
A good introduction to accounting. Make sure you read the textbook and be sure to keep up to date, otherwise this will be your worst nightmare.

The compulsory core accounting unit have a preparer perspective. It provides an introduction to basic concepts in accounting and their application for decision making by a wide range of potential users, shareholders, investment analysts, lenders, managers etc). This unit should benefit students who wish to specialise in accounting, and will also be of value to students whose primary interest lies elsewhere in the field of business.
It's OK subject, much better than other crazy core subjects

Much harder than accounting 1A mainly because of the qualitative components. If you like accounting, you will find this course interesting. Do the practice quizzes, many questions in the final exam are similar to those.
A wonderful course where the lecturers and tutors really understand students and know how to teach them. Very enjoyable as long as you keep up to date with the work!

Requires a strong foundation in ACCT1501. You study those topics that you haven't done in ACCT1A. Half theory & half journal entries so you do need to have some basic business knowledge to do well. The exam is pretty tough so study consistently definitely helps.
Not bad. Builds upon ACCT1501 content in a way that isn't dry (in most cases). If you have a good tutor that doesn't bore you also helps!

On completion the first year accounting courses seek to develop: technical competence in recording economic events in the accounting system; a critical understanding of key technical terms and concepts so as to interpret accounting information and reports in the financial press; an ability to argue a reasoned position on key questions of accounting theory and practice; and familiarity with institutional structures that affect the practice of accounting. Topics covered in this course will include accounting for the major transactions cycles, cash, receivables, inventory, non-current assets and liabilities, cash flow statements, accounting policy choice, further detail on management accounting including costing systems and budgeting, corporate governance, and professional ethics.
Interesting subject that builds on 1A. A bit difficult to understand at times and requires more work. But still great.
Decent subject, good intro to management accounting core principles which are later built on through more theoretical application in mgmt acct 2.
Avoid this subject just like avoid any MGMT subject

Although it is interesting, I feel it is taught poorly as the lecturers seem to cram everything in leaving no room to specialise in any topic and instead it is very general which means the exams are difficult since it doesn't focus on one thing.

Nothing relates to journal entries. It's a different branch of accounting. You study mostly about costing, short-term decision and a bit of performance evaluation. It's half calculation & half theory course. You need to have a deep understanding of the contents to do well as the questions are usually tricky (not to mention that the marking is so very strict). Don't ever cram this subject the last minute. I give it 5 stars because it's challenging & interesting at the same time.
Will do fine if you don't last-minute cram in the studying

This course examines management accounting practices directed towards the effective use of organisational resources and focuses on three interrelated themes: first, the design and operation of management accounting systems for planning and control; second, the role of management accounting practices in supporting effective resource management and process improvement; and, third, the manner in which these practices affect and are affected by human processes within organisations.
don't fail
gsssssssssssssssssssss

This course consists of a mixture of mathematical and theoretical aspects, providing a highly solid introduction to management accounting's overall theories and concepts. It requires continual and regular work; however, the lectures and homework exercises are extremely helpful and engaging.
Learn income tax and consolidation topics. Very challenging and definitely need a lot of practice to be able to understand what's going on. Exams are easier than expected.

A lot of unrelated topics. Quizzes are hard so you need to study consistently. The contents are not difficult but the fact that you learn very deeply along with tough assessment makes the course quite challenging to do well. Strong knowledge of journal entries from previous accounting subjects helps a lot.

Overall a great course. The only thing to worry is the exam, the questions can be quite time-consuming. Otherwise, it is a great course. Also, tips: for the weekly quiz, your mates will have the same version of quiz (with slight change in some paper but overall it is very similar) if you guys have the same tutor :)
it is a wam booster, If you find a good partner to do the group report.

To be honest, definitely one of the easier ACCT courses at UNSW. Can be a WAM booster if you put in a decent amount of effort. Auditing is all about content, theory and applying that theory to scenarios so if you stay on top of your work, it should be a breeze. I enjoyed it a lot, and the seminars were interesting and not too demanding. Making quality notes is a must!

Contents are  theoretical but exams are practical so there is a gap. Require a strong foundation of financial accounting. Practice past exams helps abit but they change the exam every semester. The key is to know how to recognise/solve different types of question (e.g. substantive test, transaction cycles, fraud, internal control).

This course examines the practice of auditing and the underlying concepts, auditors responsibilities and the audit environment. Although the focus of attention is on audits carried out under the provisions of the Corporations Law, reference is also made to other forms of audit. The course is intended to provide an overview of the audit process as it exists in Australia. Both CIS and computer-assisted audit techniques are an integral part of this unit.

This course is well taught, and focuses on important Actuarial models. It is more of a mathematical/statistical course than an Actuarial one, however all theory is applied to Actuarial problems. The tutorials are the highlight of this course. They provide a good outlet for discussion of questions. I recommend that students taking this course try to stay on top of the tutorials and the R self-tutorials.
Everything is good about this course. If someone other than Ralph Stevens was the lecturer for this course, then it would be even better because it is so hard to understand Ralph's English.

It's a great course for creative and outgoing people - their idea of 'experimentation' pushes students to their creative limits, encouraging them to undergo transformations on how they perceive art.

It doesn't go towards your WAM, so if you're looking for a quiet and relaxed course, this will be perfect! It covers the scope of transforming an everyday dull object into something that you should be proud of.

I didn't find it useful, but that was because it wasn't for me.
Interesting and broad. Great introduction to aerospace structures and builds on MMAN2400 well. It's good that it's so specialised to aircraft. A little unorganised as a course.
Fantastic, interesting, thorough course. Lecturer is very personal and endeavours to answer all questions. Useful for understanding concepts important to your career.
Challenging course but the most useful in terms of working towards a degree in medicine or working clinically. Don't fall behind or it can become severely overwhelming
Labs are really fun. Had a great tutor
Awesome course. Really interesting and great tutors. Need to always keep on top of the content or you'll get swamped on exams. If you cram for anatomy, you're gonna have a bad time....

I really enjoyed the lectures. It is worth while to going and just watching Patrick do his thing then going home to absorb what you know. It is a memory game but will set you up for all the pathology subjects in the future.

Patrick is an awesome tutor/lecturer and really makes this course. Quite challenging and lots of content to absorb, but you'll be thankful for it if you go on to do PATH in semester 2 and Year 3 because you'll be constantly needing to refer to histology knowledge.
Very well organised, good content
Co-ordinator is poorly organised and unclear to students. Content is quite interesting and the course could be a lot better if somebody else ran it.
Great course to learn about the limbs! Very concise and well structured, includes a variety of assessment formats as well which is good.

If you like the challenge of anatomy, then this course is for you. The added factor of trimesters make it the ultimate memorisation test for all med sci kids. Best thing about this course are the PhD tutors who run your labs. Absolute life savers. Worst thing is that the lectures drag on a bit.
Really interesting, useful course for anatomy and neuroscience majors. Can be quite challenging, but is quite well taught and there are lots of resources available to help.

Well taught and fairly well organised. Spot Test 2 is organised in the exam period which I'm on the fence about. Also, the assignment is unusual but interesting (good that you get to choose a topic out of a range).

The lecturing content is extremely interesting and the lecturer is very knowledgeable. The tutorials can sometimes get a bit boring as most weeks are focussed on workshopping other student's work, and sometimes only a few people within the class will contribute within the entire 2 hrs which makes the tute drag on a bit.
Please select a star rating

Really enjoyable course which is really easy to understand and pretty chill in terms of assessments too. The content isn't difficult but it is explained in thorough detail. You also get to experience lecturing from different guest lecturers from the Arts and Social Sciences faculty. Great course overall!
Enjoyable course that you will find interesting & hopefully quite easy if you were good at English in high school.
interesting range of texts studied and a lot of good discussions in tuts

excellent course structure, which discusses in depth teaching and application of literature theory across many famous poems (including Sappho's poems, HD's poems, McKay's poems etc) and also really interesting prose texts such as Jekyll and Hyde as well as Jane Eyre and Virginia Woolf's 'A Room of One's Own'. I took this course while it was taught by Prof Helen Groth, and it was truly amazing and really interesting, her lectures are really great, heaps of info on the slides and really useful resources suggested.

ARTS1031 was one of my favourite courses in the English Literature program at UNSW. As the title suggests, it covers the early modern and modern periods of English Literature and includes the likes of Pope, Jane Austin, Katherine Mansfield and Samuel Beckett, among many others. This course offers depth as well as breadth and, when it was convened by Dr Bill Walker, was thoroughly engaging and stimulating.

it was an alright course, the content was absolutely amazing but the focus was a little too much on the manifestos in the beginning, one of the tutors really pushes their personal viewpoint on some of the manifestos which potentially can dampen your experience in having the class project their own opinions in an accepting environment, but overall the content is extremely good esp towards the end of the course

Personally really love this topic even as a non-film student because it feels like every assessment is a Year 12 English analysis, and as English was the strongest subject I thrive in class discussions. The films we analysed were interesting an out of the ordinary, however I wish we didn't have an end of semester exam for it.
really boring，tutor gives really low score.
I agree with sarah!!
I don't like it :( have to read the same sentence 10 times to understand :(( readings are not fun :(( lecturer speaks too slow :( stay at home :(

Honestly this course was okay. However, I found the concepts (which were very abstract) quite tedious to study, and my tutor wasn’t really that helpful. The feedback I got on assessments was really poor and didn’t really help me improve. I thought the lecturer was really good & the lectures were really easy to follow. You might find the course a bit frustrating as it goes on, but it’s easy to do reasonably well if you go to the lectures & try to connect with the material.
I felt this course content was boring and hard to understand. Extensive readings weekly, and just overall underwhelming.

This course was fairly interesting although not as much as I had thought it would be when I picked it as an elective. The multiple choice final was a bit odd – I have never heard of theoretical arts subjects having final exams? Sometimes the reading load could be quite high. This course was the first time I had encountered a tangible level of cultural marxism at this university through an actual course – globalisation, globalism, erasure of historical identities, race, gender, etc. are all presented as unequivocally positive changes which media facilitates in the modern world in the readings and lectures. This one-sided view struck me as poor academic practice generally not characteristic of this university. Other than that the course was a let-down because it didn’t examine the ways in which media can be used as brainwashing/propaganda which is what I had hoped to be learning about – it took the view that media is neutral and users define its meaning which I thought was quite an odd and abstract way to introduce media studies to first years. The assignments are the usual first year academic skills melded with course content sort of approach which was boring for a higher year person taking this as an elective. The instructions and feedback on these assignments was fairly poor. Overall I didn’t enjoy this course as much as I had hoped to, but it wasn’t too bad in the end.

I can’t believe this is a course on offer, I have wasted my money and time on it. Absolutely not vocational and useless for the rest of my course. Assignment instructions are unclear and so is the marking making it impossible to improve or understand your short comings. Very disappointed.

Though it can be dry at times, here's a tip - actually attend/listen to your lectures, read your readings and participate in tutorial discussions. The lecturer really does try to make all the abstract theory interesting by using many practical examples and engaging with students, so it would be in your best interests to get actively involved with the content. 

From what I can see, the course syllabus has changed from previous years. It may change again in the future but for 2017, you really had to know your referencing because there were a few written tasks including an annotated bibliography, essay and critical reflection. Look carefully at the course outline and pay attention to everything to prepare for the final multiple choice test. Good luck!

It's absolute crap that this is a CORE unit for any Media student; garbage content with no two-sided arguments and all based on stupid theories that have no relevancy to the media industry other than its history. It's also ridiculous this has an exam, the content isn't worthy of an exam!! My tutor was the only reason I didn't give it a 1 star.

This course is awful as a core for media students. The assignments definitely need an update particularly the blog which is pretty much touch and go because you get no feedback or tips on how to write it. Just in general I found the subjects discussed a little useless and it's difficult to know how to go about writing them

Extremely theory based subject. Requires you to just stay up to date wit assessments and write essays based on readings. Tutorials must be attended and lecture notes made per week for easy fluent assessment tasks

This subject is pretty easy to get marks in, just pay attention in tutorials, discuss ideas in lots of detail and take lots of notes because the lectures are incredibly boring to attend/watch. This is the follow-up subject to ARTS1090 which was 2-stars for me due to the exam aspect. Best part is that there are 3 assessments and no exam. But of course, they mark you hard - and do no leave the final one to the final two nights before; 3000 words fries your brain
Shit subject, all theory. All assignments are essays.......
A really easy subject, just make sure that you pay attention in class, as I found the tutorials more helpful than the lectures in making summary notes for the final exam

Pretty good course overall - if you have a good tutor then it's really helpful. Weekly posts/responses and big final assignment - you don't get any results for these until the end of the term which makes it hard to track how you're going in the course.
Concept wasn't hard, but the tutor was a harsh marker
Interesting unit to do but the tutor was really bad. Lectures and tutorials are not related, making it difficult to put what you learnt in the lecture into practice.
Solid course, tutorials very full and students quite dumb.
Fairly okay course overall. Guest lecturers were amazing while actual lecturer was a little dull. Interesting topics though if looking for a very quick study of world history.
alright course that covers many topics, although not in a lot of depth and sometimes the organisation of the course (especially after trimesterisation) is not great

Good course overall with a good indepth summary of the 20th century. I really like the lecturer for this course (along with the guest lecturers, they were alright too). 

Highly recommended for those doing a History major.
An excellent introductory course to the more applicable elements of philisophy.
Amazing course. Very interesting with great lecturers

interesting course and and really worthwhile, the assignmetn seems deceptively short in word count but really really requires a lot of thought, do not be fooled by the seemingly 'easy looking' assignments
A very interesting course that somewhat manages to make quite complex content accessible and understandable.

Covers a range of interesting topics such as personal identity, time travel, Descartes' Meditations and more. You learn how to write good arguments and get to ask a lot of intriguing questions. Markos is a great lecturer but Michaelis needs to work on his timing (he is very easy to talk to though and get along with). Overall, a very interesting and worthwhile course.
Too much writing, and the course is dominated by fake-mandarin-beginner. you will be fail because by them
Lecturers and tutors move very fast through grammar and vocabulary, classes are too workbook-based and should involve more speaking.
Interesting subject for anyone interested in studying the Chinese language.
Good follow up from Chinese A

Loved this course, it specifically says for Chinese Background speakers, so for all those people who thought it was hard well of course because you're not background. The lecture Dr Wang is the funniest and gives great lectures. I only did this as a General Education Course but I would do Part B if I had any free electives left. My Chinese has improved very well and this was actually a course that has taught me something for the outside world when I leave university.

I went to the first lesson, the lecturer explained the course outline however once he started the actual Chinese lesson, he began teaching mandarin in MANDARIN! I immediately switched to ARTS1450, so much better.

Would give zero stars if I could. Please do not take this course if you're actually a beginner. Everyone here is pretending to be a beginner but in reality they know HEAPS of chinese. This will be detrimental to your chances of getting good marks in this course
Tutor wasn't that great and lecturer was pretty mean
An interesting subject about French!

I did this subject having done first semester Introductory French at USyd and consequently found this course quite dull. Aside from the vocab lists, there was very little to cover in terms of grammatical structures etc and so I found the course moved very slowly.
This is a very challenging class to anyone who does not have a fast absorbing memory or a predisposition to learn languages. The course is very fast  and intensive.
Could be better
Could be better
Great subject but there is no 'easing into it' which make it difficult. Despite this, the teachers are all very supportive and the content is fun and interesting.
Spanish classes rock! Best language to learn! Easy and extremely useful.
Great teachers, fun activities!

Most fun I've had in a university course so far. However, pretty hard to get over 80
All the sensei's are really nice and helpful too (Y)

Love it! If you are someone who enjoys learning new languages then you would say the same! The lecturer is very funny, lectures and tutorials are very chill, as is the case in most (beginner) language courses. From time to time, there are mentions of Kpop, so highly recommend for those who love Korean culture!
Duncan speaks way too fast and fills his slides with plenty of words which he basically re-reads to the class. Tutors have no direction in the class and everyone gets bored.

The content is interesting once you get into it and a great skill to have in criticising world politics, but if you don't want 80 page readings every week, and a fuck tone of concepts to get your head around don't do it. Every week is a bombardment of new ideas that i have never heard of, and they expect you to pick it up quickly. Penny and Will do not know how to teach, they talk super academic in lectures and half the words that come out of their mouths i have never heard of. They also make questions super hard and everything hard in general. The weightings are also really bad - 50% for 1 assignment, 50% for 1 exam, so if you fuck up one your fucked.. Also with exam, you can't bring any material in so you are supposed to know all concepts well, plus examples to demonstrate, plus evidence from scholars quotes/ideas ect, and their fancy ass names to reference in the exam... Pretty much, if your not a nerd and have a life and have to work don't do this subject, because its a lot of work

THE WORST COURSE I HAVE DONE. For a first year subject, the content is extremely difficult. I took the subject in my third year as an elective, expecting interesting debate and content...however it is based on theory alone, with hardly any mention of any contemporary IR topics. Stephen was nice, but not very engaging as a tutor and the tutorials are a waste of time, with no one having done the readings and able to participate. Perhaps people would actually do the readings if they weren't 40000 pages long and dry as anything.
This subject is shit!
Average subject overall. The lecturer and tudor Penny was literally the worst tudor I've ever had, the way she spoke and engaged with the class was just horrendous.
A very well taught course. It is a crash course in IR theory, which is highly necessary for further study in the field.
Challenging course with a heavy theory focus at times quite slow going but rewarding.
Despite the fact that the course can be interesting at times, this course is not well taught at all. Penny's voice is un-tolerable (sorry) and not well suited for a Year 1 student

Have to agree with poster below. Is somewhat interesting though can be hard to grasp. Very theoretical. Not ideally suited to to first year students despite being an introductory course. Hard to cope without copious amounts of study and without prior knowledge. Readings are around 60 pages of academic articles per week. Lectures rarely ever cover all the content presented. And though this isn't nice or relevant to subject, Penny's voice and speed of talking is so irritating that it is almost impossible to watch lectures online.
Possibly one of the worst subjects ever, made worse by the fact that one of the lecturers cough*penny*cough is so unpalatable and intolerable it's not funny
Interesting subject, just not excellently taught. Do your readings and be on top of your final project to really succeed
Excellent course! Took ARTS1811 before ARTS1810 and was glad I did because 1810 was a nightmare.
1 million times better than ARTS1810, with the course content extremely interesting! However, the tutor was quite judgmental when it came to class discussions which made me not want to participate.
A great course - applying IR theory to contemporary issues.
Was a very interesting course, with a fantastic lecturer. Covered a variety of issues and concepts. It required a deep understanding of the relevant theories, i.e. Realism, Liberalism, Marxism etc.
A rather abstract course, but can have its moments.
Great subject!! Amazing lecturer and tutors and really relevant topics

I totally love this subject! Though sometimes rethinking a different countries' society is quite complex for an international student. And obviously it's not easy to get HD in this subject on account of the overloaded work (one workbook entry each week by reading 2 long and complex articles). Nonetheless,both the lecturer and the tutor are perfectly passionate and interesting. And btw I love Durkheim!!! Lols
fun course and interesting concepts taught in the lecture (including creative writing theories), however the 2.5hr tutorials sometimes can be overly long

This subject is awesome and the lecturer is wonderful, knowledgeable, approachable and provides really helpful feedback. The assessment tasks are spread out nicely and the course is organised really well. I would take it again if I had the choice!

extremely interesting course and one of the rare, well-structured courses after trimesterisation, only two assessments/exams during the entire course, but they are substantial exams. really intriguing course content and exam questions, highly recommend it if Sean is taking it
This course was fun - 8 of Shakespeare's plays over 12 weeks. Get reading early on, but otherwise just enjoy it! The assessment tasks were pretty normal and easy enough :)

This course was great, but had a reasonable amount of reading - make sure you get the novels etc. early, & get started on them! The expanse of text types and analytical work was great - Julian Murphet convened it when I took it, and he was excellent!

Personally, I wasn’t a massive fan of this course. I enjoyed the texts but there were way too many and I felt we rushed through them, so when it came to assignments I had to do a lot of extra reading and research to understand even the basic plot of novels. it could definitely have been better, but the lecture (Dr Attridge) is really great.
Pure terrible. Don't bother
This course is amazing!!! Lecturer gave loads of resources and classes were engaging and fun!

The structure of the course is 20% group work, 40% essay and 40% final exam.

Group work is based on one of the weeks topic and you must present it in your tutorial - it's generally easy marks as long as you attempt to make it interesting while still drawing on the key points from the readings.

The essay must be written about one of the topics in the he first half of the semester - also simple and straightforward as long as you have a decent thesis/ understanding of the topic and you don't have too many pointless references.

The final exam is comprised of multiple choice,short answers and a long essay. As long as you study all the theorists and how they relate to one another, you shouldn't have any surprises.

The lectures are a little long and drawn out and everyone is expected to participate in tutorials. All in all, it was a pretty good course (even though I didn't attend most of the lectures because the weekly readings cover the same thing!)
I don't recommend this course, poor structured and all the online materials don't help much.
Enjoyable and interesting course. Also relatively easy to get D's and HD's in.
really interesting!!
The lecturer is sharp in his words but soft in his heart; he is actually kinder than his actions.

A well delivered, encompassing look at the many elements of understandings of wildlife alongside various engaging case studies that demonstrate the complexities of human/animal relations. Thom Van Dooren deploys alternative, somewhat experimental pedagogic strategies alongside strong academic content (that is also easily accessible and sourced for personal investigation) to engage with the class. Thom's strong emphasis on narratives and storytelling make lectures entertaining, informative and sought provoking. Don't miss  the opportunity to learn from a lecturer who has networked and written extensively in this area of study and who has a passion for helping students participate in his joy.
Even though you could take this course as a General Education you need background information beforehand. Make sure you study for the class test!

An improvement from ARTS2270. The lecturer, Charmaine, obviously took the feedback from ARTS2270 (she taught that course in Semester 2016) and made the lectures (and tutorials) much more engaging. I feel it was shame that I did not take much advantage of the tutorials often but the course was great. Just make sure you submit your assignments on time though. Charmaine does not have an issue to deduct marks from late submissions.
One of the best philosophy courses on offer as it deals with actually applicable content, and not just abstract concepts and theories.
A little fast paced sometimes I think they forget that this is supposed to be a non-background course. Also depends which tutor you get though!
Not bad if you enjoy learning the language
A best way to start Chinese at an Intermediate level!
A step towards the challenges of Intermediate Chinese!

Surprisingly very interesting subject, completed it over summer as a gen ed subject. 
Quite easy to complete and teachers are very helpful. Would recommend as a gen ed!
Great subject with a variety of activities. Henar and Rita are great teachers! There is a lot of content but it's worth it.

This subject is interesting! It can be difficult and there is a lot of work to do every week but it's worth it. It would be better if there was a greater focus on speaking Spanish rather than just writing and grammar.
If you did Japanese Continuers in high school, this course goes over a lot of what you did in high school in more detail

Challenging course with ongoing assessment and quizzes.
Not too difficult for those who have done hsc continuers as much of grammar is repeated.
10ish kanji to learn each week.
Lecturer friendly and tutors friendly. 
Enjoyable as lots of peer interaction.

If you continuously study and are organised and prepared, this course will be easy to do well in. You continue your learning of Japanese grammar, writing styles and vocabulary. You also learn all forms of polite speech, which can be difficult to learn and memorise. I would not recommend this course to people who have a fear of public speaking, as majority of the assessment tasks require speaking in front of the class. Although this course requires a lot of work, you do a lot of activities with other students, which makes it fun! I definitely recommend it.

Difficult subject. Complete all grammar in Japanese.
Lots of polite speech which can be tricky to learn.
Friendly staff.
Not good for people with fear of public speaking as have to do multiple assessments of speech.
Requires consistent work, but fun as activities involve other students.

Really interesting content but unfortunately the delivery/teaching of the content was very dry. The lectures involved watching lecture slides and the tutorials weren't very interactive. The content itself is very interesting and I for this reason I would recommend the subject.

The course is great, well taught by Peter Ross. It can be taken for your Development Studies, History or Spanish and Latin American studies major/minor. However, the course was made for a Development Studies... Very based on economics, I did not feel it very 'historical'

This was genuinely one of the most interesting and well put together courses I have ever done at university. I completed the course whilst Duncan McDuie-Ra was teaching it and he, and Matt the tutor were great. I read absolutely every single article this course because they were that interesting and accessible. Can't recommend the course highly enough, though I understand that Duncan no longer teaches it, so it might be different moving forward.
Brilliantly run course, with a refreshing balance of theory and a practical implementation of tools learnt throughout the course. Susanne Schmeidl as a lecturer was excellent.
He was very vague about the point of the whole subject so it didn't feel like we were focusing on any one particular angle of between the wars.

Really interesting content but dreadfully executed course. Convenor totally disengaged and did not follow own course outline. Assessed on content not covered in course materials. Tutorials entirely student run (very bad). Lecture slides and recordings not posted online, despite recording capability of room. Attendance taken at all lectures. Ridiculously harsh marker and marks never given back. throughout semester. Avoid!!!

Great course with excellent teaching, great lecturing from Dr Apoifis and some really engaging tutors + guest lecturers. A must do course for anyone interested in world politics, security matters and international relations or simply current affairs and their historical and conceptual roots

One of my favourite IR courses. It is a course where you will apply all the approaches you learned in Year 1 into International security. The lecturer, Nick Apoifis, is one of the most passionate lecturers that I have come across. Do this course if you can!
I truly enjoyed this class, although i took issue with the rudeness of the tutor. The course content is very interesting and studied with a strong link to contemporary issues.
class is wayyyyy too complicated for a 'introductory' course, do not do this class if peters is teaching.
Amanda was an excellent lecturer/tutor. Approachable, easy to work with and super supportive.
Really engaging course! What an interesting way to look at the world we live in and understand our interaction with it.

A very well structured and liberal course designed to facilitate both independent and collective inquiry into the nature of individuality and the theoretical history of philosophical thinkers concerned with thought and the human body. Melanie White is a lovely human being, she performs her passion-filled lectures with careful consideration and a quirky, loveable attitude. The subject areas are delivered with considered content for weekly readings and alongside a refreshingly high level of expectation for engagement through introspective writings or "jottings" to be done each week. Melanie will take you through the classics, made relevant to today ,and plonk you on the doorstep of fringe philosophical concepts equipped with a range of introspectively developed questions.

Don't be misled by the course name, most of it is just about Japanese culture in general and lots of it is very similar to ARTS2872 Living and Dying. There was barely any information on assessments and feedback is super vague. The lecturer didn't know how to teach or what to talk about. Classes were quiet and confusing. Just buy Sheila Jasanoff's book and save your time.
One of the best course I have taken for my History major. Zora is an excellent lecturer (and tutor) and she makes the course extremely interesting!

Fascinating subject! Highly, highly recommend. Look at a range issues of sex and sexuality at different points in history and given a number of opportunities to specialise in your interests. Assessments relevant and enjoyable. Convenor is lovely and allowed for electronic submission when not present at Uni on due date. No exam. Possibly best subject I have taken at Uni so far.

I really enjoyed this course. Dr Morrison is fantastic. The course and its texts are divided by geographical location so you address the Global North and Global South separately. There's lots of freedom with assignments which was great.

Really engaging and critical subject, lots of very interesting ideas and a lot of freedom to think through them at your own pace and in your own way. The very subjective nature of some of the content might make it difficult for some students to know what's 'correct', but that's part of why this subject is so refreshing and interesting. Andrew is also a very passionate, thoughtful, and encouraging teacher who cares a lot about what he's teaching.

Great Level 3 History course taught by an excellent and actual Historian.  It is a course for all History major students.  However, it significantly tends to lean towards those who have been studying European or US History.
Great Level 3 History course taught by an excellent and actual Historian. Just make sure that you end up in a good group as one of the assignments is a group presentation worth 20%!
incoherent
Need more courteous manners by the students
alot more focus on the chinese culture, less focus on the language
Better lecturer who has strict policies!
Amazing lecturer and great class. Took this as a gen ed and it was superb. Don't take this as a gen ed if you are not a native of very professional Spanish speaker.

There's a lot of assessments, but the group play is quite fun. It's a good idea to choose junior sensei for the assessment as it's easy marks and you won't leave it to the last minute because it's on every week. The lecturer is ok
Course is structured well but the textbook is over 10 years old. You are not taught how to do any assessments or provided with any assessment criteria or marking rubric.

A very challenging and hard course if Korean is not your first language. A large quantity of texts is studied in each class and the rythm is pretty intense. Thorough preparation before, and reviewing after every class is necessary for non native speakers. You will learn a lot as long as you are working hard for it -it mainly is a lot about personal work.
A highly rewarding course if you put in the effort. Exposes you to the realities of research and the research process.
Fantastic course. Although it deals with quite complex content, it is taught in a super interesting and approachable manner. An interest in global economics and finance does help.

Very interesting content but the teacher marks really really tough. She gives feedback like 'great assignment, excellent topic, maybe could have been a bit more narrow but still good job' and then gives you a 65. Not sure if I'm just mistaken here but I was under the impression one small negative comment like that wouldn't lose you 35 marks?
What a great subject! Vicki Kirby was the course coordinator and Noela Davis my tutor- both were awesome teachers. Very interesting
Most disorganised course ever

One of the most critical, self-aware, and engaging subjects I've ever studied. Provides a very insightful examination of what Whiteness means and how it has been constructed historically, with a particular focus on colonisation in Australia. Nature of the content means class discussions were quite central to our learning and always very interesting. Final essay at the end allows students to design their own question, so there's room to work with these big ideas. Ben is an absolute champion.
Broad scope gives you an idea of what to expect in the aircraft engineering industry. Great starting point.

The lecturer is interesting but you either love her or you hate her. I did very well with my assignments and I had an interest for safety etc, although sometimes I fell asleep during the class. The assignments included a 30% essay ( including 10% peer marking), 10% mid semester MC quiz and 15% group work. It was kind of like psychology so if you're into that type of stuff about the brain, memory etc. then this will be enjoyable for you. I do know a few people who disliked this course but its one of those things that you'll have to try out for yourself. If you're good at essay and have an interest for psychology, you'll ace this.

Great lecturer, so friendly and helpful and patient, made the course enjoyable. A lot of contents but if you keep up every week you will ace it, there shouldn't be any surprises. 
Unfortunately I think he has left the school, so don't know how it will be run from now.

The lecturer is the best person ever. Super patient and helpful, always up for a chat and willing to help students individually. The content is good quality too and interesting. Similar to FINS1613 but more aviation oriented. Assessment include 3 quizzes and 1 mid sem + finals. Overall I enjoyed the course a lot. Would highly recommend if you do not like the physics and maths alternative that aviation offers.
nice sub

The content was interesting but overall I found the course to be super disorganised which detracted from the positives. The group assignment is a waste of time and the labs are pretty straightforward but nothing too exciting. I took it because it was mandatory for my degree but would certainly not have taken by choice.

There is a lot of content one must learn in this course. Thus, one must keep up to date with this subject, in order to do well. Labs are not that difficult, but content from them should not be dismissed.

Labs were okay, lecturers were good, just keep up to date with all the lecture notes including the prac work since the the mid sems and final exam cover both these sections. However, there were no practice exam papers to use for revision.
Easy for previous biology students but interesting and well run for those who haven't done it before.

Course has alot of information but was interesting to do. I think alot of people underestimate the amount of content you need to remember but since alot of concepts covered are from HSC biology, if you did that then it shouldn't be that much of a struggle. 
There are two midsems, which I found helpful because it pretty much stopped me from cramming for finals since I had prepared my notes before hand. Labs are 3 hours long but if you finish early you can always do something else.
The course teaches you how to write scientific reports + look through journal articles and I think that's an important skill to have. There are no past papers for this course.
The labs are soooo long and boring. Lectures are relatively easy if you study
Make sure you are constantly revising throughout the semester - especially the little things.

Very straightforward course. If you did biology in high school, some of the content will be pretty easy, just a bit more detailed. 
Course manual is pretty good since it tells you everything that will happen in every lecture. 
If you happen to be in one of the first lab sessions of the week, you're most likely to get the bad samples and reagents and have your lab practicals failing. Plan your lab work because demonstrators try to get you to choose which practicals you want to do first for good time management. If you happen to have Ted as your demonstrator.. good luck. I had Jacinta and she was pretty good just group discussions were a bit slow so we'd be the last ones to leave. 
Some lecturers can really go off topic and then rush the end of the lectures.

A general and broad biology course, straightforward for hsc biology students with a slight extension on most content. For students that haven't studied biology previously it can be a bit overwhelming and I would definitely recommend utilising a text book or just getting the aid of a tutor to provide an explanation of some of the background that is skimmed over. On the whole a good course
Good subject that gives a broad understanding of biology, although may seem a little repetitive if you did Year 12 Biology. Good laboratories and good lecturers.
Waste of time if you've done high school bio or chem or BABS1201. Too many assessments worth almost nothing.
My favourite course at uni so far.. teaching and content was great

If you’re wanting to do microbiology and biotechnology, then this is the course for you. The skills you develop from the labs will be handy for you when you progress into your second year courses. The labs were 4 hours long but majority of the times you’ll end up finishing within 2-3 hours, depending how much work needs to get done.
Fun labs, great tutors, and a very interesting course. Perfect for those wanting a taste of all science majors or trying to decide on one as all are covered in at least one lab over the semester
Gives a great introduction to microbiology, biotechnology and general biological processes and their applications. Fun and interesting labs, although they can get a little long.
Very interesting course, just try to keep up with the content. It gets difficult towards the end of the semester.
Excellently run course with very interesting lecture topics. At the end can get difficult due to not very good lecturers
Some lecturers struggle a bit to convey the information, however, the labs are okay and you do learn a lot. The midsem and prac exams are insanely hard

If you're interested in doing enviromental microbiology, then this is a good subject for you - Lots of emphasis on ecology and so forth. However, if you're majoring in medical microbiology like I was, you're better off sticking to immunology because half the course will bore your socks off. First half of the course was great though, but second half was just Antarctica. Finals are a killer as well, so good luck.
A very challenging course, however crucial for anyone interested in medical microbiology. It requires a lot of memorization and study but is super interesting!

It's very very hard! But it is easy to do well in the assessments if you ask a lot of questions, i got an HD in all of them and im soo not good at stats. But the final exam is DIFFICULT bc you have to change all the computer work into written for the exam.
It's difficult, but hands down most useful subject for life sciences
Interesting lecture content and standard bio labs. Worst part is the large focus on enzyme, cofactor and molecule names; means that you'll be mostly rote learning for the exams.

Very interesting and highly organized course. The course coordinator sets the assessments out pretty fairly and all the content learned in lectures is linked to each other some way or another. There are also revision lectures to help you in understanding any content you may have trouble with.

This course can be enjoyable if you listen to instructions carefully, don't ask ridiculous question and not expect to be spoon fed. Although that may sound horribly tedious it actually helps you develop skills needed in higher difficulty university courses and in future job prospects. Just make sure you follow assessment guidelines to the 'T' or it will reflect harshly in your grades.

Content was pretty interesting, but course coordinators were generally unhelpful and they did not give us proper marking criteria for our assignments... it lacked detail... it was just really basic. Needless to say, a large majority of us didn't perform well. I should have done this course when Anne Galea was still apart of it! Learning outcomes don't even reflect what you learn in the lectures. Don't do this course unless you absolutely need it.
Generally good but the course coordinator was very unorganised which made it a bit more difficult than necessary to get assessments done.
Anyone fortunate enough to have Anne Galea as their co-ordinator is set to have a fair semester. Her lectures are well set out, labs are relevant and there is good exam preparation provided.

Practicals are long and boring and the lectures are slow. But the content itself is easy to follow on with and the exams are off the lecture slides. Easy WAM booster if you're keen as a bean for biology.

Pretty easy to get through if you go to all the lectures. Lauren Kark goes through examples thoroughly and is very helpful. Don't really understand how the handbook was marked but otherwise, the tests and exams were OK.
Interesting concepts however the amount of content is a bit overwhelming and it is not clear what information should be prioritised.
Good course if you enjoy digital signal processing. Teaching style can be hard to adapt to though (depending on lecturer). Assignments allowed for creativity.
Covers basic electronics principles and their context in biomedical applications. Some of the labs are really cool.
suck

I really enjoyed the course, but sometimes the labs ran overtime and sometimes we finished an hour early... there's a lot of content and it can be a really difficult course if you don't get on top of it early. I enjoyed the animal bio half the best, and the lecturers for the first half were much more engaging. There's really great support from all the course coordinators when you run into trouble though.

Very dry course. Interesting with the animal anatomy section, the others (plants and evolutionary stuff) were very boring and of year 10 high school standards. Easy to get good marks in labs, but SO much content. Amazing lecturer for the first 3 weeks, after that, very boring.
I did this course back in Sem 2, 2012. It was poorly managed back then. The labs were all over the place and the lectures were mediocre. I hope it has improved now!

Worst university course I have taken. Very disorganized and the lecturers and lab demonstrators aren't enthusiastic or polite. Lab experiments were pointless and the whole cohorts failed due to mistakes made by demonstrators.
Great subject, very interesting material, amazing lecturers, one of my favourite subjects. If you enjoed this subject, I highly suggest also taking "Animal Behaviour" (BIOS2061).
Loved this course so much! Very interesting content and the lecturers are so passionate it makes you want to learn. Loved the labs and the plant collection.

A heavy but interesting course that goes into detail about the major vertebrate groups. A bit disorganized at times but the lecturers are very passionate about their fields. The dissecting labs for weeks 2-5 are fun but after that, the labs are a bit tedious. The practical exam at the end is brutal.

Such a great course! It is mainly practical based, with a week long field trip to broken hill. The bulk of the course is based around a group research project which is fun and builds statistics, research and report writing skills.
The course is comprehensive and extremely interesting and well taught.
Course is easy and following the mass balances the content becomes very superficial
Disaster
Taught well.  Gives a lot of exposure to chemeng.
course is not taught very well
Great course. Clear concepts which built a solid foundation for senior years.
Good lecturer.  Sets foundation to future courses
Clear and easy to understand lectures
Great course, got a DN!
A lot of calculations, but it was fun
Great course but concepts were a bit confusing
Easy course, got a DN!
Easy course, got a HD!
Just your typical lab based course. Easy, got a HD

Honestly a good way to boost your WAM scores as part of the discipline electives requirements, but can also provide you with a bit background about pharmaceutics while meeting other students from different courses.
basically high school chemistry, very easy to get HD, tutorials and lebs help alot.

I found this course quite easy, as I had done Year 11 and 12 Chem, so I spent most of my time explaining concepts to the members of my workshop group, which lead me to have a deeper understanding of the topic

Easy course to get HD in and fairly enjoyable as well. Had slightly more content than HSC chemistry but very doable. In my course, there was a 100% pass rate before we even sat for the final exam due to the course structure. Highly recommended as a WAM booster. (If you are a medical student doing this as general educations, I guarantee this will be the highest score on your transcript)
Easy, straightforward and relaxed. Labs are fun and great, pass the labs just by getting the core skills.

Excellent subject, very straight forward. The course is composed of a lab worth 20%, which 10% is pretty much automatically awarded if you show up to all the labs to attain the "core skills". weekly online quizzes each worth 1%. mid semester multiple choice test worth 10% and finals 60%. Overall it was an enjoyable course. I did not attend any lecture and still managed to obtain a decent mark.
Fairly dry, similar to year 12 chemistry with some fun labs. Overall a necessary but not completely enjoyable subject
A little harder than CHEM1011 in terms of how the labs are paced. There's a lot more new stuff like organic and inorganic chem

Fast paced subject, particularly if you're fresh out of high school- what you might learn in a term at highschool you'll cover in a couple of days. Quite an interesting subject, most of the lecturers are passionate and keen to help, tutors are alright. You have minor assessments each week with relatively unlimited attempts, there's plenty of opportunities to pass the course, it's a little more tricky to actually get a high credit/ distinction.
Well structured, fast paced and interesting. Some of the lab questions are extended are quite challenging but the demonstrator was really helpful and nice

The lecturers are passionate and know the content. The content is broad and not as difficult when making use of the plentiful resources to help you understand. Labs are easy enough if you read the manual and staff are helpful overall.

Course is well structured and gives the student a broad exposure to chemistry. The course is ideal chemical engineering students as it overlooks thermodynamics.

Laboratory component is straightforward and teaches the students key techniques that will be useful for higher level courses.

Course is good and the content is broad. Labs can be made easier by reading through the method before hand and doing any calculations necessary before the lab. It's easy to score marks in the lab, too.
Cole is an interesting lecturer, although he does cover content fast. Kable has an interesting style of teaching, with handout sheets being discussed in class.
Tutorials are very helpful to clear up any doubts that are present.
Mid-sem test is easy as long as enough revision has been done.
Difficult but excellent lecturers. Practicals are great

Course isn't as difficult as what some people make it out to be (other than the finals). The midsems were fairly straightforward, and pretty similar to the practise one given on moodle. Lab demonstrators were nice + friendly. 

Lecturers were all really good. Beves is a good lecturer, he explained concepts well + his slides were easy to make notes with. Summaries his lectures + gives out handouts. Cole's lectures were interactive + he gave out printed copies of his notes. He was abit difficult to understand sometimes but if you refer back to the textbook you should be able to understand it. Kable covered alot of content and I felt he went abit fast but he did demonstrations + gave out handouts to do in class. 

Overall an okay course to do.

Okay subject. Content maybe be reasonably okay in the lectures but it gets difficult when you have to learn how to apply that knowledge to questions and think critically. Lab works are pretty good, demonstrators are nice. Try to plan out your lab so you can leave early or get things done on time. Beves is a pretty good lecturer, summarises previous lectures as he goes on but sometimes a little fast. Cole is sometimes hard to understand. Kable is pretty engaging in his lectures and organises his lecture slides in a good way that's easy to follow. Does handout worksheets during lectures and encourages discussion between students. 
My tutor for tutorials was very helpful. Duty tutors tend to be very busy, lots of students go there for help so get there early.

All lecturers were amazing. Labs were enjoyable however demonstrator marking was inconsistent. Final exam was hard and tested a lot of the course but marks scaled up in the end. A difficult but rewarding course overall.

A comprehensive and challenging chemistry course, there is only one test aside from finals and it is quite straightforward however the yearly is much more difficult and tests a deeper understanding so make sure you have a strong conceptual understanding as well as a good grasp of the equations.
This course it particularly useful for industrial chemistry students as it outlines a large range of industrial reactions.

More interesting and challenging than first semester chemistry, but definitely worth it! 
Labs are also more fun to do.
Better than first semester chemistry.
Babs was disgusting, other components were great...
BABS component let the course down
Stay on top of the homework assignments and labs and you should be okay with this one. Ron Haines notes are a godsend!

The majority of the labs within in the course were quite enjoyable. The lecture content was also quite interesting and easy to digest. The exception to the quality of the course was the electrochemistry component, however, this was due to the lecturer being difficult to follow, not providing clear examples, having poorly formatted slides etc.

Mainly builds on the fundamental concepts of organic chemistry that was taught in CHEM1021 as well as the water and chemical components of foods topics taught in FOOD1120. The labs were fun as you got to analyse cool things like the sucrose content in condensed milk.
A huge wam booster. Despite the endless list of assignments to do, they are all very easy to do. The lecturer is also very helpful as well.
Great subject. Fully online. Very useful and relevant. The assessments are not too difficult.

- very well structured and interesting course
- relevant for anyone's general knowledge to know about social change, issues and change mechanisms and agents
- some nuggets of wisdom from speakers from course material which was personally stimulating
- moderate-to harsh marking from tutors
- lots of online participation expected for good marks
- good for students passionate about law, change, social justice, criminology, arts, etc
- tried to get good in this course, but bit more hard work from myself, and if you're lucky easy marking from tutor, you can get well into the D/HD range.
- achieved 79

This subject was alright. There are no lecture slides, but the contents are explained through long videos which I didn't like (prefer reading over watching somebody talk). Not very engaging and the group presentations were also terrible. Tutors monitor group discussions but don't do much when your group members don't reply to any of your messages. An interesting unit with many flaws.

Although this course is part of the business school, it is not entirely business related. This is a good subject for business students who wants something different, or anyone else really who are passionate and interested in how to implement a change towards social change. We had four assignments - which involved a lot of writing (good idea to look at the course outline). It may vary, but my team was really nice and helpful and the lecturers was so lovely so i never felt stressed. I also believe that everyone's experience will differ depending on each's commitment and expectations towards the course. As a first year and being in my first semester, i struggled to keep up with all my courses. Thus i didn't exactly do all my lectures and readings in COMM1000, so i didn't get to experience it with my full potential. However looking back, it was a good subject that i did enjoy and i did quite well despite being in my first semester and lost. But that is only because i have a passion for social change. If you don't, i don't think you will enjoy it. There are definitely key learnings in this course that will definitely be fascinating for you if you do have a passion, in which you can take and implement further practically in real life! :D
It's not what I expected. Kind of wishy washy. There's no final exam but there's a lot of group work assessments. The whole course basically revolves around the social issue you pick in your group

Really poorly structured subject, heavy focus on microeconomics, assessments due every week (every other week if you're lucky). Tutors and lecturers read off a textbook at a monotonous pace, barely any assisstance offered to clarify areas of confusion. Most of the course is self-taught, the 1 hour lecture each week is pretty useless. Save yourself from the new Bachelor of Commerce at UNSW and go somewhere else
Challenging subject but it can be interesting. You need to do a lot of self-study to understand the concepts
Horrible subject. Overly difficult and poorly taught.
Just dont do this course, assignments are so broad and extremely hard for a first year course
This subject is hell and so badly taught. Needs to be adjusted.
be sure to review all your notes .. never stop doing the homework will save a lot of struggle later on in the semester for the final exam ..

This course is the first computer science course and teach in C. Even though it is 'introductory', it is wise to pre-study. If It is your first time programming (just like I was), it is fast-paced, and you need to put a lot of effort to just keep up to date and absorb the material. Once it clicks with you, it is really rewarding and fun. The lecturers and tutors are truly incredible and you should definitely ask for help whenever you're stuck on something! There are also regular one-on-one help sessions that can be a lifesaver. There are 3 assignments and the final exam has hurdles on topic arrays and linked lists. 
Tips to do well: Understand the lecture materials well (Go to tutors or help sessions if unsure), do all 1 and 2-star lab exercises and start assignments early! Never get 2+ weeks of content behind.

Loved it! I had never done any programming before this course, but I absolutely fell in love with it after this course. Andrew Taylor is such a great and funny lecturer! The labs are relevant and fun. The assignments are challenging but interesting. I wouldn't say it's an easy course, but I wouldn't say it's too hard either (I managed to get 82 DN).

Only annoyances I remember was the pacing was a bit off (sudden speed up of content near halfway through term), bugs in the labs' auto-marking sometimes, and the fact that they use C rather than Python (which would have been easier as a first language).

But those are all relatively minor nitpicks; I have mostly fond memories of this course.

I really enjoyed this course as the introduction to programming. For students with no prior experience in coding, this is a very challenging course as it really require you to adapt to a different method of learning, which is learn by practice. To do well, you need to learn and practice diligently. You can't expect to cram this. The course is taught at a pretty fast pace, so it's just really important to seek help when you need it and find answers to your confusions asap.
Awesome course! Really fundamental concepts to comp sci!

Extremely useful course, one of the best introductions to coding. From people that have years of coding experience, to those who are coming in completely fresh, each person will find a challenge and can develop a far greater understanding of programming concepts and enhance their ability to problem solve in many different environments. Keep up with the course work and you will enjoy and learn a lot from the course.
Very fun and interesting course, a nice intro to programming

It is quite a difficult subject, and requires students to stay up to date with their work. The course is divided into three assignments, 12 lab works, and 12 weekly tests, so the workload is fairly heavy.

However, once you get into the habit of staying on top of your work, it's quite an enjoyable course to take.
Can be a little difficult for first time coders but if you keep up with the work it is manageable
Assignments seem quite challenging. Needs much practice.
Easy to begin with (especially if you know how to code) but it gets pretty interesting towards the end. Very enjoyable.

Overall, 1521 is a super challenging yet rewarding course. The concepts taught are always interesting and provide a level of difficulty to even experienced coders. The resources available and the tutors are always excellent yet the lecture materials can be somewhat lack-lustre. Always attend every lab, ask questions of your tutors and keep on top of the concepts taught and this course will provide ample learning and enjoyment.
Difficult course. Needs to tale seriously to every assessment.
Super fun course once you get your head around the confusing syntax for assembly (MIPS)
Confusing course, but once you get that hang of it, you'll learn a lot!

Great foundational course for understanding basic software building skills and learning Python. The course encourag good practice such as test driven development, code review and writing with better style.

A great course overall in terms of learning opportunity and course content. Python and the object-oriented style of programming is especially useful to learn in order to apply knowledge to creating large scale applications. The teaching allows those without much previous experience to learn quickly as well as challenge even those who have programmed before.

Very good course! If you're really looking to get stuck into programming go for COMP1511 though, as it is faster. If you're just programming out of interest, you will really enjoy it! Focuses on basic C programming and problem solving.

Great introduction to computing.
This is not an easy course, but provides a great depth and get you thinking hard.
You will learn how the fundamentals of computing come together, you'll get a rigorous introduction to C programming and you'll be on your way to data structures and algorithms.

Advice: work hard, really sink your teeth into the subject matter and try to program as much as possible. Treat this course as your playground - don't sweat the marks because you'll learn better by making mistakes early on and putting your wisdom to use in later computing courses.
Great intro computing course
Interesting course, a bit difficult but manageable. You learn to solve problems in this course.
Overall an enjoyable course, assignments were hard work for the amount of marks they were worth but I learnt a lot from them.

The course material is quite interesting but is taught extremely poorly, with most exam content coming from knowledge of assembly rather than what is taught throughout the term. If the course was delivered more competently, it would have been far more enjoyable.
Worst course I've ever taken at uni.

Core computing unit. This unit will be what you make of it. If you don't do your own study and keep on top of it lectures, labs and the major project will be a nightmare. If you do stay on top of things it will be very rewarding.

The course is really fantastic in terms of preparing newer and adept programmer in how to think about writing more readable and extensible code. The course covers various new material not covered in previous first and second year courses, with interesting new topics and the ability to learn and program in Java, making a game for the second assignment which was very fun. Highly reccomend the course!
Programming in Java was alright but the final written exam was worth 60% of the total mark. Marking for the project was very harsh and didn't clearly follow the marking guidelines.
Hard course. Java programming is great though.

A very important course for every student in computer science, software engineering! It really level-up your mindset to solving problems with computer programs. Furthermore, the knowledge covered in this course is also essential for technical interviews for internships.

Extremely important course that transitions knowledge of basic C into thinking like a computer scientists, with a great new toolkit of structures and algorithms to solve more advanced problems. The labs and assignments are challenging but always interesting, and super satisfying to complete. A must do course!
Really important content! Critical to being a good computer scientist, really important for interviews at big companies!
Interesting course which greatly improved my coding efficiency
Great course which every programmer should do.
Very difficult but interesting. Focuses on problem solving. You need to practice, lots. Covers a lot of content, but it may not all be examinable.

Very useful course - covers SQL programming and theory concepts such as ER diagrams and relational algebra. The tested SQL problems are problem solving using SQL queries. I would have liked to have tutorials.

Nadine is a great lecturer. The course goes over interesting aspects of HCI, and as computer science students, it's a good idea to step outside the boundary of everyday technical coding, and try a world of creative thinking. I really do think it's a useful course to take!
Well presented and interesting content. Wasn't overly challenging and marking was consistent.

I liked it. You learn C++17 and some C++ testing/build tools like Bazel. The course doesn't assume any background in C++ (I didn't have any and still got HD) and will start off easy before getting harder. But it WILL eventually get harder with more advanced topics. There is 1 individual-assignment and 2 partner-assignments (and a final exam).
Mixed feelings

I enjoyed having Jane as a lecturer as she was engaging, funny and made the 9am lecture a bit more bearable. However, the assessments tasks for this course were poorly designed and extremely vague in what was required to achieve a good mark, my tutor was even confused by the marking scheme that was given to us due to the lack of information. There were also only 2 assessments and no final exam, which meant that each assessment weighed heavily, making it difficult to achieve a distinction/high distinction. The only positive about the assessments was the flexibility in choosing a topic that you are personally interested in. Content varied, was either interesting or painfully boring. Don't make the same mistake that I did of scheduling your tutorial on the same day as the lecture as you will have to attend the 9am lecture in order to understand the tutorial. On the plus side, you can skip readings and taking notes as the assessments are almost solely based on your own research and there is no final exam.
Really interesting subject. Would recommend making summaries as you go because it’s super content heavy

Amazing subject. Was taught by the funnest tutor ever - Ms Piper. If you end up in her class you’re one of the lucky ones. Such easy-to-understand content and really interesting at times too. If you need help with this subject from someone who’s completed it with flying colours, just search for tutors under its course code, and find me. 

Ariel :)
Super interesting and I loved the lecturers.
Extremely interesting and a good introduction to criminology. Good subject for first years, however is very content heavy. If you're interested you should be fine with the work though.
not fun don't be fooled

This is a great course and the lecturer/tutor Laura was really nice. There is a lot of content to learn but it's really interesting - it was a good mix of the history of criminology as well as current criminal justice issues such as cyber crime and state crime. If you do this course, stay on top of the readings and make sure you're thinking about examples and news stories that relate to the topics - it will make it so much easier for you when it gets to the exam because nearly every question asked for examples.

Don't pick Sanja as your tutor as she is an irrationally harsh marker. She takes marks off for the stupidest reasons such as if you cite the wrong author in your final exam. She will take not just a few marks off for that, but so much that your exam mark is reduced to a measly pass when it was well worth a distinction/HD.

Mixed feelings about this class, it was enjoyable as I chose it as an elective but I'm not sure if it taught me a whole lot. Of course part of that is my fault as I didn't take it as seriously as my required subjects but it was interesting and gave insight into such a broad field.

If you've done legal studies in high school, the content is pretty much the same. Lectures were kind of boring and guest lecturers made it difficult to study for particular topics because some didn't provide slides. Had to rely on the textbook to study for the final exam. Assessments were pretty easy, especially the 2 quizzes which were basically a free 20%. Overall it was a bit of a boring course but not too difficult.
loved it

Content very interesting however it is unclear what is required for the final exam. One of the most notoriously difficult courses in civil along with computations and soil. Understanding this subject well will set you up to understand 3502 which is far more interesting.

This will probably be the biggest waste of time you will ever embark upon. The unit on project scheduling is definitely the most useful and relevant topic. Cost estimation is so basic and is actually easier than the sorts of calculations done in 2nd year construction so I fail to see the point in including the same content again but at an easier level? Engineering economics is important to know about in general, but making us actually do financial calculations is somewhat irrelevant to real life where as engineers we would be interested in the results of such accounting calculations, not doing them ourselves. Finally inventory analysis seems odd and irrelevant. This course seems more suited to a degree in construction management, and while I guess the concepts are somewhat important in understanding real life engineering construction and management it’s just a bit painful to go through as a course. Overall you can do very well in this course, it’s not hard it’s just boring.

Many students find this difficult or boring but it’s a very important subject for those wishing to do geotech in real life. The theoretical groundings this course provided often directly link to the work done in practice for geotechnical engineers and the equations introduced can be used directly to check the validity of computer analysis of real life problems. The lab and tutorial attendance/bonus marks should be seen as easy marks. The quizzes and final exam will often spin the content in a slightly different way, so understanding the actual concepts rather than just how to solve a problem is very important.

The course comes in two parts: geology, which is not in the final and finishes after the midsem, and applied geotech, which extends previous work in soil mechanics into much more exciting applications like piles, footings and walls. The joy of the open book final is negated by its incredible difficulty, not me or one person I know fully finished the final exam, yet I still got a HD so don’t worry too much, it’s designed to be that difficult. Get a good group to do the two-part fieldwork assignment with. You need to go map some rock geology which can be done in one day if you get there early and know what you are doing. On another day you need to do a self-guided walk looking at rock structures (fun) which will take at least 4 hours. While the lecturer in the geology part of the course might seem to be rambling about lecture slides filled with pictures it’s actually quite important and has helped me in the field for industrial training in geotech.

well structured and interesting. It might take  a lot of your time when doing project, but it was interesting.
Well taught and structured. One of my favourite courses at uni.

Great subject - full of maths if you like math, if you don't this subject isn't for you. Not engineering level hard but it definitely works your analytical skills.

Going in to the course, I was worried because of the negative reviews on here, however, I actually found this subject to be quite interesting and particularly enjoyed the case studies as they were applicable to the real world. I only attended 1 lecture and viewed the rest online, however, Siobhan is a great lecturer and you can tell that she is incredibly passionate about teaching policy. She's also extremely friendly and is enjoyable to listen to. I also didn't find it necessary to listen to every single lecture as there are only 2 essay-based assessments that focus on content covered in a particular week. I personally found the concepts to be relatively straightforward and easy to understand as it is mostly basic politics. Assessments were relatively easy to score good marks in, as long as you understood the concept and knew how to use case examples to back up your essay. I ended up with a HD without doing extensive study and because there is no final exam. Only downside to the course was the fieldwork component which I personally found to be kind of pointless, especially since it's not marked; however, it counts as 2 tutorials so you can miss out on a few tutes without any issues.
